text: Well, I can only accuse the Fed of hubris, not of doing the wrong thing all the time nowadays. Maybe they did the wrong thing for the previous decade or especially in 2021 when they could have been a little bit more hawkish. But if the problem really is, as I have set it out, which is that the control problem has no solutions, given this current state, again, putting my chaos theory hat on, then it's not that the Fed is messing it up now or that it's doing a great job. It's more that it's a bit out of their control. It was much easier the other way. You could if inflation was structurally low, it wasn't that hard to kickstart the economy by pushing up the leading indicators of the economy, stock prices, asset prices, improving the shape of the yield curve and so on. Going the other way, if the delays are, as I say, they are, of course, the delays are hard to specify, then it's much harder because you don't get the desired effect to inflation pushing it down until you smash growth. And so I think they had an easy position where if the delays are, as I say. States, it was much easier to stimulate than it is to withdraw stimulation.
